    Background

    Palliative Decision Making


    In the US, emphasis is placed on the patient's autonomous wishes

    Proxy decision makers are often relied on when a patient lacks decisional capacity

    Proxy decision making is associated with negative outcomes

    Azoulay et al., 2005; Cameron et al., 2016; Radwany et al., 2009; Schenker et al., 2012

    nursing.jhu.edu
    Define proxy decision makers:
    Negative outcomes include stress, depression, feelings of guilt, and decision regret.
    An advance directive remains the gold standard, but only about 1/3 people fill them out (Flarey 1991). They are also not always adhered to.

    Winter Maxwell Thayer, MSPH

    Background

    Ideal decision partners

    1. Relationship with patient
    2. Willing to fill supportive roles
    3. Willing to participate in decision making
    4. Emotional capacity to participate
    5. Understands patient’s condition
    6. Demonstrates self-efficacy

    The processes and mechanisms decision partners use to support patient decision making are not well understood

    Gray et al., 2019; Zeliadt et al., 2011

    nursing.jhu.edu
    These are characteristics of decision partners identified in a recent concept analysis by Gray and colleagues

    Winter Maxwell Thayer, MSPH

    Background

    Prostate cancer

    An estimated 174,650 incident cases in 2019

    Out of every 100 cancers

      77 will be confined to the prostate

      13 will have spread to nearby lymph nodes

      6 will have metastasized elsewhere in the body

    Only 1/3 patients with metastases survive 5 years

    Howlader et al., 2019

    nursing.jhu.edu

    Winter Maxwell Thayer, MSPH

    Background

    Utility Theory

    Choices involve trade offs

    Utility is satisfaction derived from an experience

    Provides a conceptual and mathematical framework for this study

    Samuelson (1938)

    nursing.jhu.edu
    Samuelson's tautology.

    Purpose and aims

    Purpose

    To address an evidence gap by characterizing the processes and mechanisms through which decision partners contribute on behalf of patients palliative anti-cancer treatment decision making


    To develop a tool informed by utility theory to quantify patient preferences for palliative anti-cancer treatment

    nursing.jhu.edu

    Winter Maxwell Thayer, MSPH

    Purpose and aims

    Aims

    1. Explore the processes and mechanisms through which decision partners support decision making

    2. Develop and pilot a discrete choice experiment that measures preferences for palliative anti-cancer treatment


      This research will be conducted within an ongoing randomized trial of a decision aid (CHAMPION)

    R01 NINR6483-01A1

    nursing.jhu.edu

    Winter Maxwell Thayer, MSPH

    CHAMPION Trial

    CHAMPION: Purpose and sample

    Cancer Health Aid to Manage Preferences and Improve Outcomes through Navigation (CHAMPION)

    Testing an interactive decision aid delivered by community patient navigators-nurse teams

    Planned sample of 158 dyads, 9 month follow-up

    Univ. of Virginia (Dr. Jones),  Johns Hopkins Univ. (Dr. Wenzel),  Virginia Commonwealth Univ. (Dr. Brown)

    nursing.jhu.edu

    Winter Maxwell Thayer, MSPH

    CHAMPION Trial

    Study flow

    Inclusion:

    • Age ≥ 18 years
    • Advanced prostate cancer
    • Life expectancy > 6 months
    • Karnofsky Performance Scale ≥ 60
    • Understands English

    Exclusion:

    • Severe psychiatric issues
    • Prior malignancy within 3 years

    Supplementary

    Derivation of choice probabilities

    We are interested in creating a mathematical model of the choice that an agent makes.

    Train (2003) provides the following formulation. Let $y$ denote the choice of an agent, and divide the factors that cause the choice into $x$ observed and $\epsilon$ unobserved factors.

    Train, 2003, pp. 3-5

    nursing.jhu.edu

    Winter Maxwell Thayer, MSPH

    Supplementary

    The model is deterministic in that if all $x$ observed and $\epsilon$ unobserved factors were observed the choice would be fully determined, but probabilistic in that $\epsilon$ is not observed.
    $\epsilon$ is considered random with density $f(\epsilon)$. We define a function to relate the choice to the observed and unobserved factors, $y = h(x, \epsilon)$. The probability that an agent chooses $y$ given the $x$ observable $P(y | x) = Prob(\epsilon \text{ s.t. } h(x, \epsilon) = y)$

    Train, 2003, pp. 3-5

    nursing.jhu.edu

    Winter Maxwell Thayer, MSPH

    Supplementary

    To make this model usable, we define an indicator function, $I[h(x, \epsilon) = y]$ as 1 when true and 0 when false. The probability that the agent chooses $y$ is the expected value (mean) of the indicator function over all possible values of the unobserved factors $\epsilon$. $$\eqalign{P(y|x) = Prob(I[h(x, \epsilon) = y] = 1) \\ = \int I[h(x, \epsilon) = y] f(\epsilon)d\epsilon}$$

    Train, 2003, pp. 3-5

    nursing.jhu.edu

    Winter Maxwell Thayer, MSPH

    Supplementary

    Closed form solution: $$P=\frac{e^{\beta\prime} x}{1 + e^{\beta\prime} x}$$

    Train, 2003, pp. 3-5

    nursing.jhu.edu

    Winter Maxwell Thayer, MSPH

    Supplementary

    Extension to $j$ options: $$P_{ni}=\frac{e^{\beta\prime} x_{ni}}{\sum_j + e^{\beta\prime} x_{nj}} = 1$$

    Train, 2003, p. 41

    nursing.jhu.edu
